The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 One person was killed and two people were seriously injured in two incidents of reckless driving on Wednesday. Santosh Shaw, 18, a resident of the railway colony in Behala, died and Arjun Pandit, 25, was injured on Tollygunge Circular Road around 2 pm when an unidentified private bus knocked them down. Pandit, a resident of New Alipore, was admitted to MR Bangur Hospital, where his condition was stated to be critical. The driver escaped with the vehicle. 

 n the other accident, 20-year-old Soma Chakraborty, a resident of Salt Lake, fell off a private bus on route 45 around 11 am at the Ultadanga crossing. Police said the mishap occurred after the driver slammed the brakes. The driver was arrested and the vehicle impounded.

 Ganesh Pramanik, a Railway Protection Force constable, attempted suicide on Wednesday morning by shooting himself with his firearm at the Uluberia barracks of the force. The constable, in his late thirties, was rushed to Uluberia State General Hospital, from where he was shifted to SSKM Hospital. His condition was stated to be serious. Police found a suicide note, in which Pramanik said no one should be held responsible for his death. 

 A 37-year-old man, Zakeer Hussain, was murdered by his second wife, Tanuja Bibi, on Wednesday morning in Gopalnagar, North 24-Parganas. Tanuja, after attacking Zakeer with a chopper, went to the local police station and surrendered. She told police that Zakeer had lied before marrying her a few months ago. ?I recently came to know that he was still in regular contact with his earlier wife,? she said.

 A 50-year-old woman was killed and two school-going children were injured on Wednesday morning when a speeding Tata Sumo knocked them down on Howrah-Uluberia Road. The accident took place when Amala Ganguly was on her way to a nearby primary school. She was taken to a local healthcare unit, where doctors pronounced her dead. The injured children were hospitalised and their condition is stable. The driver, who fled, had lost control of his car.

 One person was arrested in a market in Maniktala and 31 parrots were seized from his possession on Wednesday. Maniktala police station officers said they had a tip-off about Mohammad Mustaque, who had brought the birds to the market to sell them. ?We pretended to be customers and netted him,? said one of the officers.

 Police commissioner Prasun Mukherjee and deputy commissioner (traffic) Arun Sharma met state chief secretary Ashok Gupta on Wednesday to discuss measures to be taken on December 15, date of the proposed meeting of a combined forum of sympathisers of the CPI-ML (Maoist) on the Maidan. 

 Health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra on Wednesday asked nursing staff to be more polite with patients. He was addressing a gathering at Sisir Mancha on the 14th prize distribution ceremony of the West Bengal Nursing Council.

